
[1]imbitter

   IMBIT'TER, v.t. [in and bitter.] To make bitter.

   1. To make unhappy or grievous; to render distressing. The sins of
   youth often imbitter old age. Grief imbitters our enjoyments.

   2. To exasperate; to make more severe, poignant or painful. The sorrows
   of true penitence are imbittered by a sense of our ingratitude to our
   Almighty Benefactor.

   3. To exasperate; to render more violent or malignant; as, to imbitter
   enmity, anger, rage, passion, &c.
